Bea and I don‚Äôt agree now but as a writer she was a role model once upon a time - and Suzanne Moore, Deborah Orr‚Ä¶ Even Julie Burchill! And then, to me, they shape shifted. They became the very subjects of their earlier critiques.

Questionable (from my perspective) feminists have always existed. I stopped being confused about this as a teenager when I read Andrea Dworkins Right Wing Women and Bea Cambells book on Tory women whose title that I forget.
@RozKaveney The older I get the more I think about those meetings. I found them in City Limits and came on my own. I was just 20.

I‚Äôll never forget the coat hanger. And I‚Äôll always connect the coat hanger to the manipulation of fear around gender difference. Bad blood. But I‚Äôll always think about joy. And hope. And the promise of a better gendered life. Good blood.

It all started as a kid when I asked my step mum why that magazine had a coat hanger dripping with blood on its front cover - and why did it have such a weird name (Spare Rib). And all these decades later and I‚Äôm worrying again about the coat hanger.

These days I want to do all I can to ensure that trans researchers get to work on trans. My job is to move over. I don‚Äôt think that I became a professor because of doing work on trans so early, though it certainly helped.

These projects weren‚Äôt ‚Äòsupported‚Äô by trans researchers, they were made by them. And while I always strive to assist them to build their careers through  for instance named publications, grant writing support, I, of course. benefit the most. I get promoted. Invited. Named.

The institution were excited-cutting edge, newsworthy, perfect for EDI auditing. It was an absolute no from me. Never. The success of my trans‚Äô projects were all because of the trans researchers - the wonderful @NotRightRuth for example.

I‚Äôd built up community relationships. I costed in activist groups as consultants. I employed trans and queer women. But it started to feel different. On getting my professorship it was assumed by the panel that I would become Professor of Transgender Studies.

I began to work on citizenship and critiques of rights based politics. I found I loved writing and began to get published (a lot!) I won more bids. Was invited to events. Got promoted. I had a profile. I was a cis woman. I was working on trans.

I did talk about my positionality but briefly and in what I now think was a very weak way. It was 2004, the GRA had passed. I got funding to look at the GRA. On this project I began to think a lot about doing the work as a cis woman.

Still no one raised my being cis. Other people in gender studies and sociology began to focus on trans issues in PhDs. My amazing friend @zowiedavy who I began to have this - and so many more - conversation with. I finished my PhD and wrote my first book.

People with so much joy and With significant trauma and mental health issues. So many people wanted to talk. For hours. There were so many more people I couldn‚Äôt interview. Something was shifting. Nadia had won Big Brother. People wanted to talk. And be heard.

I stayed for hours. For dinner. Into the evenings. I was doing repeat interviews so back I went. For almost a year. I also spoke to women who were more familiar to me, lesbian trans women, musicians, performers. And bus drivers and women without jobs.

I‚Äôd never spoke to a straight trans women before. Women who lived and loved their wives of decades but were definite they weren‚Äôt lesbian. Women who desired and were desired by straight men. Women whose politics were so different to mine. I didn‚Äôt know any Tories or even Liberals

‚ÄòReal life test‚Äô, public outings and job losses, loosing family and children. Violence. Abuse. Stigma. Shame. This was miles away from Chain Reaction. And I went to meetings and conferences - GENDES. Voice workshops. Discos. Ball gowns. Fancy hair and even fancier make up

But it worked. It was *all* about self determination and bodily autonomy. And i began to think about legal and medical practices - institutional regulation. I knew about the politics of performance and gender subversion. I went on to learn so much more.

Risk assessments didn‚Äôt exist and I travelled around the UK on the train alone, went to peoples houses. Met in bars or cafes. I interviewed 50 people-trans men and women. I‚Äôd go from an interview with a Drag King in Highgate one day to a country conservative councillor the next.

My plan was around subversive genders - it was about the London stuff.  For funding I had to broaden it out and it came to include trans women. I didn‚Äôt think about being cis. No one asked me - until much later - about being cis. It‚Äôs unreal to think that now.
